# Claude Model Selection and Prompting Protocol

When writing prompts, agent instructions, or Anthropic/Bedrock API calls, follow the
model-specific guide. If any detail below might be stale, fetch the live doc before
answering — do not answer from memory:

- Fable 5: <https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/prompting-claude-fable-5>
- Opus 4.8: <https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/prompting-claude-opus-4-8>
- Sonnet 5: <https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/prompting-claude-sonnet-5>

## Which model to use (switch when the task changes)

| Task | Model |
|------|-------|
| Hardest, long-horizon, ambiguous, or multi-agent work; overnight autonomous runs | `claude-fable-5` |
| Default frontier work: coding, knowledge work, review; fallback target for Fable 5 refusals | `claude-opus-4-8` |
| High-volume production coding/agentic workloads where cost and speed matter | `claude-sonnet-5` |
| Simple, speed-critical tasks (classification, routing, extraction) | `claude-haiku-4-5-20251001` |

Fable 5 is not the default upgrade path; Opus 4.8 is. Fable 5 runs safety classifiers
(offensive cyber, bio, reasoning extraction) that can return `stop_reason: "refusal"`;
configure fallback to Opus 4.8.

## Fable 5 (claude-fable-5)

- Adaptive thinking always on; no `thinking` budgets; summarized-only thinking output.
- Turns run much longer; adjust client timeouts and prefer async checking over blocking.
- Strong instruction following: steer with one brief instruction, not enumerated lists.
  Over-prescriptive prompts written for older models degrade output; prune them.
- Never instruct it to echo or explain its internal reasoning in the response; that
  triggers `reasoning_extraction` refusals. Read summarized thinking blocks instead.
- For long runs, add: "Before reporting progress, audit each claim against a tool
  result from this session. Only report work you can point to evidence for."
- Anti-overplanning: "When you have enough information to act, act."
- Anti-scope-creep at high effort: "Don't add features, refactor, or introduce
  abstractions beyond what the task requires."
- Avoid surfacing remaining-context counts; if unavoidable, add "You have ample
  context remaining. Do not stop, summarize, or suggest a new session."
- Give the reason behind a request, not only the request; provide a memory file for
  lessons across runs; use fresh-context verifier subagents over self-critique.
- Effort: `high` default, `xhigh` for capability-sensitive, `medium`/`low` routine.

## Opus 4.8 (claude-opus-4-8)

- Thinking is OFF unless you pass `thinking: {type: "adaptive"}`.
- Effort: start `xhigh` for coding/agentic; minimum `high` for intelligence-sensitive
  work; `max` can overthink. At `xhigh`/`max`, set max_tokens around 64k or higher.
- Follows instructions literally, especially at low effort: state scope explicitly
  ("apply to every section, not just the first").
- Favors reasoning over tool calls; raise effort or explicitly instruct tool use.
- Spawns fewer subagents by default; state when delegation is desirable.
- Verbosity calibrates to task complexity; positive style examples beat prohibitions.
- Design default: cream background, serif display type, terracotta accent. To vary:
  specify a concrete visual direction, or have it propose 4 directions first.
- Code review: severity filters ("only high-severity") lower recall because they are
  obeyed literally. Prompt for coverage first, filter in a later step.

## Sonnet 5 (claude-sonnet-5)

- Adaptive thinking ON by default; disable with `thinking: {type: "disabled"}`.
  Manual `budget_tokens` returns a 400 error.
- Non-default `temperature`, `top_p`, or `top_k` returns a 400 error. Get variety via
  prompting (e.g. propose multiple directions), not sampling parameters.
- New tokenizer emits roughly 30% more tokens for the same text; max_tokens values
  tuned for Sonnet 4.6 may truncate output (`stop_reason: "max_tokens"`).
- Effort mapping when migrating: Sonnet 5 `medium` is comparable to Sonnet 4.6 `high`;
  Sonnet 5 `high` is comparable to Sonnet 4.6 `max`. Use `xhigh` for hardest tasks.
- With thinking disabled it reaches for tools less; add an explicit tool-use nudge.
- Literal instruction following, verbosity calibration, code-review coverage-first
  prompting, and design-variety guidance same as Opus 4.8 above.

## Cross-model rules

- Prompts are model-specific: when switching a feature to a different Claude model,
  re-check effort, thinking config, max_tokens, and sampling parameters against the
  target model's guide before shipping.
- Raise effort rather than prompting around shallow reasoning.
- Remove scaffolding that forces interim status messages; current models self-report.
